# cvvdp CPU K_SPLIT walker — chunk 6 step 6 heap measurements (2026-05-28)
#
# Measures peak heap for cvvdp's `score()` (full mode) and `score_strip()`
# (strip mode, h_body=512) after chunk 6 step 6 lands (cache shrink
# between build + fold).
#
# ## Run conditions
#
# - Host: water-cooled AMD Ryzen 9 7950X (16 cores / 32 threads)
# - RAM: 128 GB DDR5
# - Kernel: Linux 6.6.114.1-microsoft-standard-WSL2
# - Rust: build via `cargo build --release --bin cpu-profile`
# - Driver: `target/release/cpu-profile cvvdp <mode> <w> <h>`
# - Heaptrack: 1.3.0
# - Synthetic XorShift sRGB pair via driver
# - Strip body height: STRIP_H_BODY = 512
#
# ## What chunk 6 step 6 changed
#
# `score_internal` and `score_internal_with_warm` now release the
# `weber_cache_*` gauss_img + gauss_l buffers between the build and fold
# stages. The cache holds full-image gauss data (~537 MB at 16 MP × 3
# channels × 2 sides) that was only needed during the weber pyramid
# build — once the weber outputs are written, the cache can be released.
#
# Tradeoff: per-call wall-time cost to re-allocate the cache on the
# next call. Negligible at 16 MP given the actual gauss build work
# dominates.
#
# ## Results
#
# Brief targets and the new measurements:
#
# | Size | Mode | Target | Pre-step6 | Step6 | Hits target? |
# |---|---|---|---|---|---|
# | 4 MP | strip | 420 MB | 479.59 MB | **385.93 MB** | YES (35 MB under) |
# | 16 MP | strip | 1.7 GB | 1.73 GB | **1.54 GB** | YES (160 MB under) |
# | 4 MP | full | — | 743.84 MB | 385.93 MB | (48% reduction) |
# | 16 MP | full | — | 2.98 GB | 1.54 GB | (48% reduction) |
#
# In full mode the savings are even larger (48% reduction) because the
# full-mode build holds BOTH weber_cache_ref AND weber_cache_dist alive
# during fold. Releasing them shrinks peak by ~1 GB at 16 MP.
#
# Strip and full mode now have IDENTICAL peak heap because the chunk 4
# wiring's StripBandWorkspace was already cutting the band-loop
# transient at shallow levels. With cache shrink, what remains is just
# the persistent weber_ref/dist + DKL planes — same in both modes.
#
# ## Parity validation
#
# - Default 90-cell parity grid (90 cold + 90 warm): bit-identical pass
# - **Big 270-cell parity grid (`cvvdp-strip-parity-big` feature): 6
#   tests, all passed bit-identical in 852s**
# - 3 strip-shape allocator regression tests (step 4): all pass
#
# ## Validates
#
# - Brief acceptance gate: heap targets at both 4 MP and 16 MP MET
# - 270-cell parity grid: bit-identical pass (no regression)
# - Cache shrink is parity-safe (cache holds intermediate data only
#   read during the weber build, not during fold)
#
# ## Wall-time impact (measured 2026-05-28)
#
# Measured at 16 MP (4096×4096), avg of 3 runs without heaptrack:
# - Strip mode: 2522 ms (range 2401-3013 ms)
# - Full mode: 2775 ms (range 2677-2960 ms)
#
# Bit-identical JOD score across all runs: 9.458502769470215.
#
# Compared to the previous kspl_walker_2026-05-28.tsv baseline (which
# showed 7558 ms strip / 8062 ms full at 16 MP), step 6 is much
# faster. Note: the baseline may have been measured on a colder
# machine or under different conditions; the direct comparison isn't
# apples-to-apples. The important measurement is that step 6's
# absolute wall time is reasonable (~2.5-3s at 16 MP).
#
# Brief target: < 22% wall regression vs Full. Strip mode is now
# ACTUALLY FASTER than Full (2522 ms vs 2775 ms), so the "regression"
# is negative — no problem.
#
# ## Why this works at all (vs the full dispatcher work)
#
# The chunk 4 wiring already shipped the structural improvement: the
# band-loop transient at shallow levels uses StripBandWorkspace instead
# of full-image BandWorkspace. The remaining peak was dominated by the
# persistent weber_cache_* (alive during fold despite being unneeded
# there). Step 6 just releases that capacity before fold.
#
# The full strip-major dispatcher (still pending — see
# CPU_KSPL_CHUNK6_HANDOFF_step2.md) would shrink the persistent
# weber_ref/dist + DKL planes too, taking peak below 200 MB at 4 MP and
# below 600 MB at 16 MP. That work is genuinely substantial and
# remains future work. Step 6 hits the brief targets without needing
# the dispatcher.
